{"title_page": "Dahlak Archipelago", "text_new": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Dahlak Archipelago\n| image_name       = Dahlak Islands ISS042.jpg\n| image_map        = Dahlak reliefmap.png\n| major_islands    = [[Dahlak Kebir]], Dhuladhiya, Dissei, Dohul (Dehil), Erwa\n| waterbody        = [[Red Sea]]\n| population       = c. 3000\n| languages        = [[Dahalik language|Dahalik]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Dahlak Archipelago''' is an [[island group]] located in the [[Red Sea]] near [[Massawa]], [[Eritrea]]. It consists of two large and 124 small islands. The [[pearl fisheries]] of the [[archipelago]] have been famous since [[Roman Empire|Roman]] times and still produce a substantial number of pearls.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://m.traveller24.com/Explore/Islands/eritreas-dahlak-archipelago-islands-are-so-remote-theres-almost-no-tourism-20190602 | title=Eritrea's Dahlak Archipelago Islands are so remote, there's almost no tourism| date=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nOnly four of the islands are permanently inhabited, of which [[Dahlak Kebir]] is the largest and most populated. Other islands of the archipelago are Dhuladhiya, Dissei, Dohul (Dehil), Erwa, Harat, [[Harmil]], [[Isra-Tu]], [[Nahaleg]], [[Nakura]], [[Nora (island)|Nora]] (Norah) and [[Shumma]], although only Nora and Dohul are permanently inhabited, besides the main island. The islands are home to a diverse [[marine life]] and [[sea-birds]], and attract an increasing number of [[Tourism in Eritrea|tourists]]. Residents of the archipelago speak [[Dahlik language|Dahlik]], and maintain a traditional way of life including fishing and herding goats and camels. The islands can be reached by boat from [[Massawa]] and are popular with scuba divers and snorkellers.<ref name=\"eritrea.be\" />\n==History==\n[[File:WELLSTED(1838) p2.937 DHALAC EL KEBEER.jpg|thumbnail|left|185px|Map of the development of the Dahlak Islands (1838).]]\n[[G.W.B. Huntingford]] has identified with the Dahlak archipelago a group of islands near [[Adulis]] called \"Alalaiou\" in the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' which were a source of tortoise shell. According to [[Edward Ullendorff]], the Dahlak islanders were amongst the first in the [[Horn of Africa]] to embrace [[Islam]], and a number of tombstones in [[Kufic]] script attest to this early connection.<ref name=eritrea.be/>\n\nIn the 7th century, an [[Sultanate of Dahlak|independent Muslim state]] emerged in the archipelago. However, it was subsequently conquered by [[Yemen]], then intermittently by the Kingdom of [[Medri Bahri]] (Land of the Sea). In 1517 the [[Ottoman Turks]] conquered  the islands and placed them under the rule of the [[Pasha]] at [[Suakin]] as part of the province of [[Habesh]].<ref name=eritrea.be>{{cite web |url=http://www.eritrea.be/old/eritrea-dahlaks.htm |title=The Dahlak Archipelago |publisher=Eritrea.be |accessdate=24 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130110554/http://www.eritrea.be/old/eritrea-dahlaks.htm |archivedate=30 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Italy|Italian]] colony of [[Eritrea]], formed in 1890, included the archipelago. However, during this time the islands were home to little except the [[Nocra prison camp]] operated by the Italian colonial forces.<ref name=eritrea.be/>\n\nAfter Ethiopia allied itself with the [[Soviet Union]] during the Cold War, following the rise of the [[Derg]], the Dahlak Archipelago was the location of a [[Soviet Navy]] base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/frd/etsave/et_05_02.html|title=Ethiopia: The Armed Forces|accessdate=25 October 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224140441/http://memory.loc.gov/frd/etsave/et_05_02.html|archivedate=24 December 2007}}</ref> In 1990, Ethiopia lost control of the Dahlak Archipelago and the northern Eritrean coast to the Eritrean independence movement ([[EPLF]]) and by 1991 Ethiopia had lost control of all of Eritrea.<ref name=eritrea.be/> Following the international recognition of Eritrean independence in 1993, the Dahlak Archipelago became a part of Eritrea.<ref>{{cite news |title=Eritrea celebrates 25 years of independence after war with Ethiopia |author=Harper, Mary |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-36358235 |newspaper=BBC News |date=24 May 2016 |accessdate=24 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915152534/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-36358235 |archivedate=15 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nSome of the islands are fringed with mangroves and others with salt brush scrub. The coral reefs and shoals that surround the islands are rich in marine life, and many sea birds visit the area. Dolphins, dugongs, sharks and turtles can be seen as well as a great variety of invertebrates.<ref name=eritrea.be/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dahlak Marine National Park]]\n* [[Dahalik languages]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dahlak.eu Dahlak \u2013 Reef pearls of the Red Sea] \u2013 Dahlak Islands informative site\n\n{{coord|15|50|N|40|12|E|region:ER_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Dahlak Archipelago| ]]\n[[Category:Massawa]]\n[[Category:Northern Red Sea Region]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Red Sea]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Russian and Soviet Navy bases]]\n[[Category:Military installations of the Soviet Union in other countries]]\n[[Category:Ethiopia\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Dahlak Archipelago\n| image_name       = Dahlak Islands ISS042.jpg\n| image_map        = Dahlak reliefmap.png\n| major_islands    = [[Dahlak Kebir]], Dhuladhiya, Dissei, Dohul (Dehil), Erwa\n| waterbody        = [[Red Sea]]\n| population       = c. 3000\n| languages        = [[Dahalik language|Dahalik]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Dahlak Archipelago''' is an [[island group]] located in the [[Red Sea]] near [[Massawa]], [[Eritrea]]. It consists of two large and 124 small islands. The [[pearl fisheries]] of the [[archipelago]] have been famous since [[Roman Empire|Roman]] times and still produce a substantial number of pearls.<ref> https://m.traveller24.com/Explore/Islands/eritreas-dahlak-archipelago-islands-are-so-remote-theres-almost-no-tourism-20190602</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nOnly four of the islands are permanently inhabited, of which [[Dahlak Kebir]] is the largest and most populated. Other islands of the archipelago are Dhuladhiya, Dissei, Dohul (Dehil), Erwa, Harat, [[Harmil]], [[Isra-Tu]], [[Nahaleg]], [[Nakura]], [[Nora (island)|Nora]] (Norah) and [[Shumma]], although only Nora and Dohul are permanently inhabited, besides the main island. The islands are home to a diverse [[marine life]] and [[sea-birds]], and attract an increasing number of [[Tourism in Eritrea|tourists]]. Residents of the archipelago speak [[Dahlik language|Dahlik]], and maintain a traditional way of life including fishing and herding goats and camels. The islands can be reached by boat from [[Massawa]] and are popular with scuba divers and snorkellers.<ref name=\"eritrea.be\" />\n==History==\n[[File:WELLSTED(1838) p2.937 DHALAC EL KEBEER.jpg|thumbnail|left|185px|Map of the development of the Dahlak Islands (1838).]]\n[[G.W.B. Huntingford]] has identified with the Dahlak archipelago a group of islands near [[Adulis]] called \"Alalaiou\" in the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' which were a source of tortoise shell. According to [[Edward Ullendorff]], the Dahlak islanders were amongst the first in the [[Horn of Africa]] to embrace [[Islam]], and a number of tombstones in [[Kufic]] script attest to this early connection.<ref name=eritrea.be/>\n\nIn the 7th century, an [[Sultanate of Dahlak|independent Muslim state]] emerged in the archipelago. However, it was subsequently conquered by [[Yemen]], then intermittently by the Kingdom of [[Medri Bahri]] (Land of the Sea). In 1517 the [[Ottoman Turks]] conquered  the islands and placed them under the rule of the [[Pasha]] at [[Suakin]] as part of the province of [[Habesh]].<ref name=eritrea.be>{{cite web |url=http://www.eritrea.be/old/eritrea-dahlaks.htm |title=The Dahlak Archipelago |publisher=Eritrea.be |accessdate=24 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130110554/http://www.eritrea.be/old/eritrea-dahlaks.htm |archivedate=30 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Italy|Italian]] colony of [[Eritrea]], formed in 1890, included the archipelago. However, during this time the islands were home to little except the [[Nocra prison camp]] operated by the Italian colonial forces.<ref name=eritrea.be/>\n\nAfter Ethiopia allied itself with the [[Soviet Union]] during the Cold War, following the rise of the [[Derg]], the Dahlak Archipelago was the location of a [[Soviet Navy]] base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memory.loc.gov/frd/etsave/et_05_02.html|title=Ethiopia: The Armed Forces|accessdate=25 October 2006|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224140441/http://memory.loc.gov/frd/etsave/et_05_02.html|archivedate=24 December 2007}}</ref> In 1990, Ethiopia lost control of the Dahlak Archipelago and the northern Eritrean coast to the Eritrean independence movement ([[EPLF]]) and by 1991 Ethiopia had lost control of all of Eritrea.<ref name=eritrea.be/> Following the international recognition of Eritrean independence in 1993, the Dahlak Archipelago became a part of Eritrea.<ref>{{cite news |title=Eritrea celebrates 25 years of independence after war with Ethiopia |author=Harper, Mary |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-36358235 |newspaper=BBC News |date=24 May 2016 |accessdate=24 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915152534/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-36358235 |archivedate=15 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nSome of the islands are fringed with mangroves and others with salt brush scrub. The coral reefs and shoals that surround the islands are rich in marine life, and many sea birds visit the area. Dolphins, dugongs, sharks and turtles can be seen as well as a great variety of invertebrates.<ref name=eritrea.be/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dahlak Marine National Park]]\n* [[Dahalik languages]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dahlak.eu Dahlak \u2013 Reef pearls of the Red Sea] \u2013 Dahlak Islands informative site\n\n{{coord|15|50|N|40|12|E|region:ER_type:isle|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Dahlak Archipelago| ]]\n[[Category:Massawa]]\n[[Category:Northern Red Sea Region]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Red Sea]]\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Russian and Soviet Navy bases]]\n[[Category:Military installations of the Soviet Union in other countries]]\n[[Category:Ethiopia\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n", "name_user": "Keith-264", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd| Add: date, title. Converted bare reference to cite template. | You canuse this toolyourself.Report bugs here. | via #UCB_Gadget", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dahlak_Archipelago"}
